summary: Are taking birth control pills really bad for your health?
question: Are taking birth control pills really bad for your health?
answer:
I mean, with any medication it’s a risk benefit balance. All medications can seriously damage your health if you have the right risk factors, if they’re not the correct prescription for your needs, or if you exceed the recommended dose (the dose makes the poison after all). And all medications can be incredibly beneficial to health when used correctly, in the right dose, for a person with few risk factors who needs it (even cocaine and heroin - aka diamorphine - have valid clinical uses that can improve health in the right context).

Taking the birth control pill can be incredibly beneficial for a person’s health, which is why it is used in the first place. Firstly, it’s intended to prevent pregnancy which carries its own host of serious health risks, it can help manage the symptoms of conditions such as polycystic ovary syndrome and endometriosis, and also help women with difficult, painful, irregular and heavy periods manage their menstrual cycle.

But all medication comes with risks, and this is why context is very important. If you are overweight, a heavy smoker, a heavy drinker, have hypertension or have a family history of certain diseases, then the benefits of the birth control pill will probably be outweighed by the risks and your doctor will probably recommend an alternative treatment. It’s a case by case basis, and the more information your doctor has the best treatment they can provide - which is the case in all circumstances, with any medication. It’s why a pharmacist will ask you a whole host of questions when you buy something over the counter, even cough medicine or paracetamol.
